{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2be06f4f-ed6b-4db9-bebf-af4abdf23ca6","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace with a `stdio` server entry that runs your project via `dotnet run`:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard MCP transport for local servers).\n- **`command` / `args`** — uses `dotnet run` so it builds and launches automatically.\n- Make sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout using the MCP protocol (e.g., via the `ModelContextProtocol` or `Microsoft.Extensions.AI` SDK).\n\nOnce saved, VS Code will detect the server and prompt you to start it in agent mode. You can also add `\"env\"` for environment variables if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c208f021-a75a-48d5-adf1-dd9bb6c8dde9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user said they built it. They're just asking how to configure `mcp.json`. I should provide the configuration guidance.","outputTokens":305,"requestId":"CC30:19D0BE:7DA891F:8BFE553:69EAC17D"},"id":"62bab14f-bc4e-40ca-bb74-abc636647b8c","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:04:09.925Z","parentId":"49dea548-a6e7-4418-83fa-159d5a8de09f"}
